phase2.explanation:
Conceptual review — no broken code!

Common misconception: "I should never catch exceptions — I'll just let them crash."

Actually: You should catch exceptions and handle them gracefully, but only when you can do something useful with them.

Bad pattern:
try {
    riskyOperation();
} catch (Exception e) {
    // Empty catch — swallowing exceptions!
}

Good pattern:
try {
    riskyOperation();
} catch (IOException e) {
    // Log the error and recover
    System.err.println("IO Error: " + e.getMessage());
    // Could use a default value
}

Remember: Don't swallow exceptions!

Another misconception: "File I/O is always slow."

Actually: Buffered streams and NIO make I/O much faster. Reading 1MB at a time is faster than reading 1 byte at a time!
